label.value: abnormal cell cycle arrest in meiotic prophase I with clustered telomeres

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the first meiotic nuclear division is arrested in prophase I under conditions where arrest does not normally occur, and with telomeres clustered at the spindle pole body. Telomere clustering at the SPB indicates that the cell has reached or passed the pachytene stage.

label.value: bent spindle during meiosis I

value.value: A spindle phenotype in which the meiotic spindle is not straight, but instead forms an angle where microtubules from opposite poles interdigitate, during meiosis I.

label.value: multiple spindles during meiosis II

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which a cell contains more than one meiotic spindle per nucleus during the second meiotic nuclear division.

label.value: spindle collapse during meiosis I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a short meiotic spindle assembles during meiosis I, and may begin elongation, but does not elongate normally or completely, and eventually collapses. Upon collapse the spindle may break or shrink.

definition.value: Sister chromatids may separate in meiosis I due to problems with either cohesion or kinetochore attachment to microtubules. Therefore consider also annotating to 'abnormal attachment of spindle microtubules to kinetochore involved in homologous chromosome segregation' (FYPO:0000209), 'decreased meiotic sister chromatid cohesion' (FYPO:0002093), or 'merotelic kinetochore attachment during meiosis I' (FYPO:0005638).

label.value: abnormal homologous chromosome arm segregation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which homologous chromosome segregation is abnormal along the chromosome arms.

label.value: increased duration of Rad52 focus presence during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A cell phenotype in which sites at which the protein Rad52 accumulates remain present for a longer time than normal during the meiotic cell cycle. Normally, Rad52 foci form during prophase I but disappear before metaphase I.

label.value: normal mitotic spindle morphology

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, or structure of all or part of the mitotic spindle is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: Note that an abnormal nuclear envelope organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal nuclear envelope morphology.

label.value: normal microtubule cytoskeleton organization during meiosis I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which microtubule cytoskeleton organization is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during meiosis I. Microtubule cytoskeleton organization is the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising microtubules and their associated proteins.

label.value: abnormal meiotic centromere clustering during meiotic prophase I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which centromere clustering takes place during meiotic prophase I, and remains incomplete. Normally, centromeres and SPBs associate during prometaphase I, but not earlier.

label.value: normal meiotic centromere clustering during meiotic prometaphase I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which centromere clustering is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type during meiotic prometaphase I.

label.value: microtubule bundles present in decreased numbers at spindle pole body during meiosis I

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which cells contain fewer microtubule bundles associated with the spindle pole body than normal during meiosis I.

label.value: abnormal microtubule depolymerization

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which microtubule depolymerization, i.e. the removal of tubulin dimers from a microtubule, is abnormal.

label.value: decreased rate of microtubule depolymerization involved in meiotic centromere clustering during meiotic prophase I

value.value: A cellular process in which depolymerization (i.e. removal of tubulin dimers) of microtubules occurs at a lower rate, or speed, as part of centromere clustering during meiotic prophase I.

label.value: abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton organization during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A phenotype that affects the organization of the microtubule cytoskeleton during all or part of the meiotic cell cycle. Microtubule cytoskeleton organization is a cellular process that results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of cytoskeletal structures comprising microtubules and their associated proteins.

definition.value: Consider annotating to 'abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton' (FYPO:0002399), but note that an abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in a physically abnormal microtubule cytoskeleton.

label.value: normal microtubule bundle

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the amount, distribution, and morphology of microtubule bundles are normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: abolished protein localization to medial cortical node, with protein mislocalized to cytoplasm during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the medial cortical nodes is abolished, and the protein is present in the cytoplasm instead, during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein level in actomyosin contractile ring during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of a protein in the actomyosin contractile ring is lower than normal during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: Use this term for cases where the relative abundance of one or more specific proteins in the proteasome is decreased, altering the proteasome stoichiometry. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased RNA level during cellular response to leucine starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of RNA measured in a cell during a cellular response to leucine starvation is lower than normal. Total RNA or a specific RNA may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription. We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased RNA level during cellular response to leucine starvation

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of RNA measured in a cell during a cellular response to leucine starvation is higher than normal. Total RNA or a specific RNA may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription. We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: loss of viability upon amino acid starvation

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a smaller than normal proportion of cells in the population remains viable when cells the population are subject to starvation for one or more amino acids.

definition.value: Use this term to annotate experiments in which a culture is grown under glucose-depleted conditions, and then the number of cells viable enough to form a colony upon return to conditions supporting vegetative growth is measured and compared to wild type.

label.value: abolished cell cycle arrest in mitotic G1 phase in response to leucine starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the occurrence of cell cycle arrest in response to leucine starvation does not occur; arrest normally occurs in G1 phase.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

label.value: normal growth on iron

value.value: A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing iron ions.

label.value: decreased mitochondrial respiratory chain complex assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the occurrence of assembly of one or more mitochondrial respiratory chain complexes is decreased.

label.value: unbundled spindle during mitotic prophase

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed during mitotic prophase (in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle) in which the mitotic spindle has two poles, but spindle microtubules (MTs) are not aligned into parallel or anti-parallel bundles. Instead, MTs extend in random directions from the asters, and the spindle does not elongate.

definition.value: In images of thin spindles, polar microtubules may appear not to reach continuously from pole to pole.

label.value: normal protein localization to mitotic spindle midzone during prophase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the mitotic spindle midzone during prophase is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). The mitotic spindle midzone is the area in the center of the mitotic spindle where the spindle microtubules from opposite poles overlap.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: mitotic sister chromatid separation in absence of mitotic spindle

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mitotic sister chromatid separation begins when the mitotic spindle is not present.

label.value: abnormal microtubule bundle formation during mitotic spindle assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which microtubule bundle formation that takes place as part of mitotic spindle assembly, and which normally results in a parallel arrangement of microtubules, is abnormal.

label.value: abnormal actomyosin contractile ring maturation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which actin contractile ring maturation is abnormal.

label.value: abnormal mitotic chromosome movement towards spindle pole

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which movement of chromosomes from the center of the mitotic spindle towards the spindle poles is abnormal. This normally takes place during mitotic anaphase A.

label.value: abnormal homoserine O-acetyltransferase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of homoserine O-acetyltransferase activity is abnormal.

label.value: abolished homoserine O-acetyltransferase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which homoserine O-acetyltransferase activity is absent.

label.value: increased protein localization to microtubule plus-end

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the plus ends end of microtubules is increased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased microtubule binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the binding of a protein to one or more microtubules occurs to a greater extent than normal. The affected protein may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

definition.value: This term can be used for any interaction with actin filaments that is affected by a mutation, whether or not the mutated gene product is one of the interacting proteins. We recommend noting which proteins were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to medial cortical node during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the medial cortical nodes is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal septation initiation network signaling

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which septation initiation network signaling is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). SIN signaling is mediated by the small GTPase Ras, and results in the initiation of contraction of the contractile ring at the beginning of cytokinesis and cell division by septum formation.

label.value: increased level of AP sites in DNA

value.value: A phenotype in which the number of apurinic and ayprimidinic (collectively, AP) sites detected in DNA is greater than normal. An AP is a deoxyribose sugar with a missing base, and is formed by the enzymatic removal of a damaged base.

label.value: small mononucleate vegetative cell

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a cell contains one nucleus and has an abnormally low volume.

label.value: small multinucleate vegetative cell

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetative cell has an abnormally low volume and contains more than one nucleus.

label.value: inviable small multiseptate vegetative cell

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetative cell is inviable, has an abnormally low volume, and contains more than one septum.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'inviable cell population' (FYPO:0002059) or one of its descendants.

label.value: abolished protein localization to medial cortical node during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the medial cortical nodes is abolished during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: inviable after spore germination, multiple cell divisions, swollen, elongated cell

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce a cell that has a greater length, diameter, volume, and length:diameter ratio than normal, and undergoes two or more rounds of cell division and then dies.

label.value: abolished endodeoxyribonuclease activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which an endodeoxyribonuclease activity is absent.

label.value: loss of viability following cellular response to ionizing radiation

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a smaller than normal proportion of cells in the population remains viable after exposure to ionizing radiation.

definition.value: Use this term to annotate experiments in which a culture is grown with exposure to UV light, and then the number of cells viable enough to form a colony upon return to absence of UV is measured and compared to wild type.

label.value: increased 5'-deoxyribonuclease (pyrimidine dimer) activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of 5'-deoxyribonuclease (pyrimidine dimer) activity is increased.

label.value: increased deoxyribonuclease (pyrimidine dimer) activity during cellular response to UV

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of deoxyribonuclease (pyrimidine dimer) activity is increased during a cellular response to ultraviolet light.

label.value: normal 5' deoxyribonuclease (pyrimidine dimer) activity during cellular response to UV

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of 5' deoxyribonuclease (pyrimidine dimer) activity is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) during a cellular response to ultraviolet light.

label.value: abolished protein localization to nucleus, with protein mislocalized to cytoplasm, during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the localization of a protein to the nucleus is abolished, and the protein is present in the cytoplasm instead, during the meiotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal Mei2 nuclear dot formation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which Mei2 nuclear dot formation is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: sensitive to transplatin

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to transplatin. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of transplatin that allows wild type cells to grow.

label.value: normal growth on N-methyl-N'-nitro-N-nitrosoguanidine

value.value: A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing N-methyl-N'-nitro-N-nitrosoguanidine (MNNG).
